[[ファイル:Iki tsukiyomishrine haiden.jpg|サムネイル|Distant view of the haiden]]
'''Tsukiyomi Shrine''' (つきよみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kokubuhigashi-fure, Ashibe-chō, {{ill|lt=Iki|Q861519|WD=Q861519|1=Iki, Nagasaki}}, {{ill|lt=Nagasaki Prefecture|Q169376|WD=Q169376|1=Nagasaki Prefecture}}. {{ill|lt=Tachibana Mitsuyoshi|Q11544184|WD=Q11544184|1=Tachibana Mitsuyoshi}} identified it as an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki shrine|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}} ({{ill|lt=myōjin taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), but this is considered incorrect<ref name="#1">Ashibe Town History Editorial Committee, ''Ashibe Town History'' (Ashibe Town, 1978)</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The current enshrined deities are three: {{ill|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto, Tsukuyumi-no-Mikoto, Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|1=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto}}. All three are the same deity.

The original deity was a “mountain deity,” but after Tachibana Mitsuyoshi’s identification, {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|1=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto}} came to be regarded as the enshrined deity<ref name="#1"/>.

=== History ===
Its origin before {{ill|lt=Enpō|Q1145735|WD=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} is unknown. In Enpō 4 ({{ill|lt=1676|Q7628|WD=Q7628|1=1676}}), Tachibana Mitsuyoshi, who investigated Shikinaisha on {{ill|lt=Iki Province|Q1052938|WD=Q1052938|lt=Iki Island|1=Iki Province}} by order of the {{ill|lt=Hirado Domain|Q3034453|WD=Q3034453|1=Hirado Domain}}, identified this shrine as “Tsukiyomi Shrine,” a Shikinaisha myōjin taisha. On June 1 of the same year, domain lord {{ill|lt=Matsura Shigenobu|Q11531889|WD=Q11531889|lt=Matsura Shigenobu|1=Matsura Shigenobu}} dedicated a stone shrine and one wooden mirror as {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532|1=Shintai}}, and it was treated as a Shikinaisha for some time. Before that, however, it had no notable ritual facilities and was simply called “Yama no Kami” (mountain god). Mitsuyoshi had identified it as a Shikinaisha because the place was called “Kiyotsuki,” but it was also called “Fukatsuki,” whose origin is thought to be “fukafuchi”<ref>''Iki no Kuni Jinjaki''.</ref>. Therefore Mitsuyoshi’s judgment is considered mistaken, and the original Tsukiyomi Shrine is held to be {{ill|lt=Hakozaki Hachiman Shrine (Iki)|Q111442063|WD=Q111442063|lt=Hakozaki Hachiman Shrine|1=Hakozaki Hachiman Shrine}}<ref name="#1"/>.

It is said that one of the “Tsukinobe stones” (moon-delay stones), which {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}} is said to have placed against her abdomen during the {{ill|lt=Conquest of the Three Han|Q11249435|WD=Q11249435|1=Three Han Campaign}} to delay childbirth, was dedicated here, but its whereabouts are now unknown.

At present, local residents including {{ill|lt=ujiko|Q125562175|WD=Q125562175|1=Ujiko}} and worshippers from outside the island maintain and improve the shrine buildings and grounds.

